Introduction

Is there a correlation between ones' 3x3 solve time and other events' solve times?

1) Data Collection + Parsing¶

Let's clean up the data. The WCA provides several CSV files, containing information encoded as needed. You can find more info on the dataset here: https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/results/misc/export.html

1i) Checking for duplicates:¶

Let's look at the Results table. This will have information on every solve recorded at every WCA competition, for each competitor and event. Data is entered and verified by WCA officials after each competition, but just to be sure, let's check for duplicates.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd

results_iter = pd.read_csv('data/WCA_export_Results.tsv', 
                           sep='\t', 
                           chunksize=50000)

df = pd.concat(results_iter, ignore_index=True)

#group by every solve to check for duplicates
group = df.groupby(['competitionId', 'personId', 'eventId', 'roundTypeId', 'best', 'average', 'value1', 'value2', 'value3', 'value4', 'value5']).count()

print("Number of rows:", len(df))
print("Number of (non-duplicate) rows:", len(group))

1ii) Solve formats and excluded events¶

Solves are recorded in different formats, depending on the event and the number of competitors present at that round. Most solve sessions are calculated one of two ways: the average of 5 solves (with the best and worst solve excluded from the average calculation), or the mean of 3 solves. These are denoted by the formatIds 'a' or 'm', respectively. But for some bigger cubes, such as a 7x7x7 cube, the best of X solves is calculated, where X is 1, 2, or 3 (this is also its formatId in the table).

The results for blindfolded solves and 3x3 Fewest Moves are calculated differently, which affect the representation of other data, so filter out those solves too for now. For these solves we will have to

The Magic and Master Magic no longer have WCA competitions held for them because they were too simple of puzzles with too few distinct solutions to make it worth competing for. Here's a list of all events, and their corresponding id used throughout the datasets.

1iii) Invalid solves¶

From the WCA Results Database Export, values that are 0 or negative can be interpreted as follows:

  • The value -1 means DNF (Did Not Finish).
  • The value -2 means DNS (Did Not Start).
  • The value 0 means "no result". For example a result in a best-of-3 round has a value of 0 for the value4, value5, and average fields.

Additionally, all solve time values are given in centiseconds (100 centiseconds = 1 second), so divide all values by 100. For shorthand notation, the following denotation will be used from hereon out:

  • Average of 5: Ao5
  • Mean of 3: Mo3
  • Best of X: BoX
In [3]:
#Format ids of Ao5/Mo3 solves
avg_ids = ['a', 'm']

#anything with a -1 in the "best" column means that average is invalid (no matter what formatId), so filter on that first
df = df[(df['best'] > 0)]

#doing isin() a lot is slow so make a boolean column for if a solve session is an Ao5/Mo3 or BoX
df['isAvg'] = list(df['formatId'].isin(avg_ids))

#Put BoX data in average column to make calculations easier
df.loc[~df.isAvg, 'average'] = df.loc[~df.isAvg, 'best']

#if a row's 'average' col is <= 0, it's an invalid solve session; remove it.
df = df[df['average'] > 0]

#Times are given in centiseconds; divide by 100
df['average'] = df['average'].apply(lambda x: x / 100)
df['best'] = df['best'].apply(lambda x: x / 100)

2) Data representation + management¶

2i) Grouping the data¶

Group the data by storing the results of those who competed both in 3x3 and the other event. The large amount of NaN values pertains to many reasons, but the two main ones are:

  • The event was not offered at the competition (usually the case for smaller competitions or remote areas). In fact most competitions do not host all events; usually only the more popular competitions that are known to attract a wider audience do so (such as Regional/World championships)
  • The person did not compete in that event at the competition. Of course, not everyone will be interested in every puzzle.

3ii) Data transformation

Our data is heavily skewed to the right, which makes sense if you think about it. Lots of novice cubers don't stay interested for that long.

Let's apply common transformations for right skewed data. These are the square root, log, and inverse transformations.

In [45]:
import numpy as np

for ev, dft in with_333.items():
    dft['333sqrt'] = dft['333'].pow(0.5)
    dft[ev+'sqrt'] = dft[ev].pow(0.5)
    
    dft['333log'] = np.log10(dft['333'])
    dft[ev+'log'] = np.log10(dft[ev])
    
    dft['333inv'] = dft['333'].pow(-1.0)
    dft[ev+'inv'] = dft[ev].pow(-1.0)

3iii) How effective was each transformation?¶

We'll calculate the Pearson-Fisher skew coefficient of each transformation and get the mean of each transformation's coefficients over all events. Also plot the distribution of solves for each event with it's respective 3x3 solve.

But instead of doing this for all events and ending up with 48 plots, let's plot the distributions for the 5 most popular events.

In [53]:
def getlen(event):
    dft = with_333[event]
    return len(list(dft['333']))

#List of keys sorted by participation in event
popular_evs = with_333.keys()
In [55]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statistics import mean
from scipy import stats

plt.rcParams['legend.loc'] = "lower right" 

#Collect coefficient values for each transformation
ps_norm = []
ps_sqrt = []
ps_log = []
ps_inv = []

#Helper function: get name corresponding to event id ev_id
def get_evname(ev_id):
    return all_events.at[ev_id, 'name'].replace(' ', '\n')
    
#5x4 grid of plots (5 most popular events x 4 transformations)
fig, axs = plt.subplots(12, 4, figsize=(20, 20))

for graphs_row, event in enumerate(popular_evs):
    dft = with_333[event]
    normal, sqr, log, inv = dft[['333', event]], dft[['333sqrt', event+'sqrt']], dft[['333log', event+'log']], dft[['333inv', event+'inv']]
    
    def pearson(df):
        x3 = np.array(df.iloc[:,1])
        ev = np.array(df.iloc[:,-1])
        
        p3 = stats.skew(x3)
        p_ev = stats.skew(ev)
        
        return (p3, p_ev)
    
    pn3, pnev = pearson(normal)
    psq3, psqev = pearson(sqr)
    pl3, plev = pearson(log)
    pi3, piev = pearson(inv)
    
    ps_norm.extend([pn3, pnev])
    ps_sqrt.extend([psq3, psqev])
    ps_log.extend([pl3, plev])
    ps_inv.extend([pi3, piev])
    
    #Limit 5 most popular events
    if graphs_row < 13:
        #Plot each transformation
        sns.histplot(data=normal, kde=True, ax=axs[graphs_row][0])
        sns.histplot(data=sqr, kde=True, ax=axs[graphs_row][1])
        sns.histplot(data=log, kde=True, ax=axs[graphs_row][2])
        sns.histplot(data=inv, kde=True, ax=axs[graphs_row][3])
        
        #Label the row with the event name
        axs[graphs_row][0].set_ylabel(get_evname(event))

        #Annotate each plot with its skew coeff.
        axs[graphs_row][0].annotate(text=("$P_{333}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % pn3 + "$P_{" + f"{event}" + "}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % pnev), 
                                    xy=(.65, .77), xycoords='axes fraction')

        axs[graphs_row][1].annotate(text=("$P_{333}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % psq3 + "$P_{" + f"{event}" + "}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % psqev), 
                                    xy=(.65, .77), xycoords='axes fraction')

        axs[graphs_row][2].annotate(text=("$P_{333}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % pl3 + "$P_{" + f"{event}" + "}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % plev), 
                                    xy=(.65, .77), xycoords='axes fraction')

        axs[graphs_row][3].annotate(text=("$P_{333}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % pi3 + "$P_{" + f"{event}" + "}=$" + "%0.7f\n" % piev), 
                                    xy=(.65, .77), xycoords='axes fraction')
    
   

#Set the title of each column (each transformation)
axs[0][0].set_title("$Time, P_{mean}=" + f"{mean(ps_norm)}$")
axs[0][1].set_title("$\sqrt{Time}, P_{mean}=" + f"{mean(ps_sqrt)}$")
axs[0][2].set_title("$\log_{10}(Time), P_{mean}=" + f"{mean(ps_log)}$")
axs[0][3].set_title("$Time^{-1}, P_{mean}=" + f"{mean(ps_norm)}$")

#Configure layout of figure
fig.tight_layout(rect=[0.03, 0.03, 1, 0.95])
fig.suptitle('Distribution of select event solve times of competitors whom participated in both 3x3 and the event,\n their transformations, and Fisher-Pearson skewedness coefficients', fontsize=16)
fig.show()

So it looks like the log transformation yields the least skewed data, on average. Let's roll with that.
